07441nam a22018135i 9780691227160DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912271607 a10.1515/97806912271602doi  a(DE-B1597)635174  a(OCoLC)1340656600  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN57.P45b.S646 2023 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a808.8/03829221142231 aSpence, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Return of Proserpina :bCultural Poetics of Sicily from Cicero to Dante /cSarah Spence. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b3 b/w illus. 1 map.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tMap. Sicily -- tIntroduction: Negotiating Empire -- t1 The Straits of Messina -- t2 Drepanum and the Limits of the Aeneid -- t3 Venus’s Other Son -- t4 Claudian, Etna, and the Loss of Proserpina -- t5 The Redemption of Proserpina -- t6 Quando n’apparve una montagna -- t7 Purgatorio, Etna, and the Empire of Love -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tA NOTE ON THE TYPE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSicily and the strategies of empire in the poetic imagination of classical and medieval EuropeIn the first century BC, Cicero praised Sicily as Rome’s first overseas province and confirmed it as the mythic location for the abduction of Proserpina, known to the Greeks as Persephone, by the god of the underworld. The Return of Proserpina takes readers from Roman antiquity to the late Middle Ages to explore how the Mediterranean island offered authors a setting for forces resistant to empire and a location for displaying and reclaiming what has been destroyed.Using the myth of Proserpina as a through line, Sarah Spence charts the relationship Western empire held with its myths and its own past. She takes an in-depth, panoramic look at a diverse range of texts set on Sicily, demonstrating how the myth of Proserpina enables a discussion of empire in terms of balance, loss, and negotiation. Providing new readings of authors as separated in time and culture as Vergil, Claudian, and Dante, Spence shows how the shape of Proserpina’s tale and perceptions of the island change from a myth of loss to one of redemption, with the volcanic Mt. Etna playing an increasingly central role.Delving into the ways that myth and geography affect politics and poetics, The Return of Proserpina explores the power of language and the written word during a period of tremendous cultural turbulence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLatin literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAchaemenides.  aAchilleid.  aActium.  aAeneid.  aAfter the Empire.  aAllegory.  aAllusion.  aAnchises.  aAnius.  aBoldness.  aBuddhism.  aCaesura.  aCaieta.  aCallimachus.  aCanticle.  aCareer.  aCeuta.  aClaudian.  aConvivio.  aDe Inventione.  aDe Oratore.  aDe doctrina christiana.  aDe rerum natura.  aDevolution.  aDiction.  aDigression.  aDionysiaca.  aDivine Comedy.  aElegiac.  aEmbellishment.  aEmpedocles.  aEnna.  aEnnius.  aEtiology.  aEuippe.  aEuryalus.  aEvocation.  aExcursus.  aFasti.  aGens du pays.  aGervase of Tilbury.  aHelenus.  aHermeneutics.  aHildesheim.  aIn Verrem.  aInque.  aItalus.  aLivy.  aLocus amoenus.  aLucretius.  aLusus Troiae.  aMnestheus.  aNarrative.  aNescio.  aNisus and Euryalus.  aNovum.  aOccitans.  aOvid.  aPalinurus.  aPeter of Eboli.  aPhilippic.  aPoetry.  aPolyphemus.  aPompey.  aPriam.  aPrimar